06915nam a22014535i 9780691223537DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912235377 a10.1515/97806912235372doi  a(DE-B1597)609923  a(OCoLC)1289368166  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aARC0100002bisacsh04a307.341609443609034qOCoLC223/eng/20230216  aNR 87202rvk0(DE-625)rvk/130128:1 ada Costa Meyer, Esther, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDividing Paris :bUrban Renewal and Social Inequality, 1852–1870 /cEsther da Costa Meyer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b60 color + 115 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The President, the Emperor, and the Prefect -- t2. Requiem -- t3. Streets and Boulevards -- t4. Water -- t5. De Profundis -- t6. Disenchanted Nature -- t7. The Periphery -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tPhotography and Copyright Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA groundbreaking work of scholarship that sheds critical new light on the urban renewal of Paris under Napoleon IIIIn the mid-nineteenth century, Napoleon III and his prefect, Georges-Eugène Haussmann, adapted Paris to the requirements of industrial capitalism, endowing the old city with elegant boulevards, an enhanced water supply, modern sewers, and public greenery. Esther da Costa Meyer provides a major reassessment of this ambitious project, which resulted in widespread destruction in the historic center, displacing thousands of poor residents and polarizing the urban fabric.Drawing on newspapers, memoirs, and other archival materials, da Costa Meyer explores how people from different social strata—both women and men—experienced the urban reforms implemented by the Second Empire. As hundreds of tenements were destroyed to make way for upscale apartment buildings, thousands of impoverished residents were forced to the periphery, which lacked the services enjoyed by wealthier parts of the city. Challenging the idea of Paris as the capital of modernity, da Costa Meyer shows how the city was the hub of a sprawling colonial empire extending from the Caribbean to Asia, and exposes the underlying violence that enriched it at the expense of overseas territories.This marvelously illustrated book brings to light the contributions of those who actually built and maintained the impressive infrastructure of Paris, and reveals the consequences of colonial practices for the city's cultural, economic, and political life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planning-Sanitation. 0aCity planning-Social aspects. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aAlgeria.  aAmbivalence.  aAnnexation.  aBanlieue.  aBoulevard du Crime.  aBourgeoisie.  aBurial.  aCemetery.  aColor theory.  aCommodity.  aCreative work.  aCultivar.  aDiscrimination.  aEngraving.  aEthnic group.  aFaubourg.  aFontaine du Palmier.  aFortification.  aFrench colonial empire.  aFrench intervention in Mexico.  aGenerosity.  aGeologist.  aGeorges-Eugène Haussmann.  aGraphic arts.  aHaussmann's renovation of Paris.  aHenri Lefebvre.  aInfrastructure.  aInsurgency.  aJean-Jacques Lequeu.  aJean-Marie Morel.  aJules Ferry.  aJuly Monarchy.  aLac Daumesnil.  aLes Halles.  aLighting.  aLouis Philippe I.  aLouis Veuillot.  aLouviers.  aMacadam.  aModernity.  aNapoleon III.  aNapoleon.  aNorthern Suburbs.  aOurcq.  aPaleontology.  aPatrice de MacMahon, Duke of Magenta.  aPersonal life